The TypeScript strict mode is using `exactOptionalPropertyTypes: true`. This means that if you have an optional property `chessPiece?: string`, you can't assign `undefined` to it explicitly. In my WhatIfMutation interface, I defined:

```typescript
export interface WhatIfMutation {
  action: WhatIfMutationAction;
  commitId?: string;
  title?: string;
  chessPiece?: string;
  estimatePoints?: number;
  rcdoNodeId?: string;
}


```

With this setting, optional properties can either be absent or have their declared type, but not explicitly set to `undefined`. In WhatIfPanel.tsx, I'm conditionally assigning values to `estimatePoints` and `chessPiece`, but when the condition isn't met, I'm explicitly setting them to `undefined`, which violates the strict type checking.

The solution is to use conditional spreading instead—only including each property in the object when it actually has a value. This way, the properties simply won't exist on the object rather than being set to `undefined`.

```

typescript
const mutation: WhatIfMutation = {
  action: "MODIFY_COMMIT",
  commitId: modifyCommitId,
  ...(modifyField === "estimatePoints" ? { estimatePoints: parseInt(modifyValue, 10) } : {}),
  ...(modifyField === "chessPiece" ? { chessPiece: modifyValue } : {}),
  ...(modifyField === "rcdoNodeId" ? { rcdoNodeId: modifyValue } : {}),
};
```

Now I need to apply this same pattern to the WhatIfPanel component.

